   {:e #blake3 "67a13b9806700bb8d6f19685ef4ff82b03e46507173c959df17a147e062c95b1" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "Session entity: :task/t-695cf74a; Session entity: :task/t-526e562e; Session entity: :task/t-c8f06727; SYNTHESIS: The build-lock problem is the tip of a massive iceberg. What we need is not just 'edit/verify separation' but the FIRST PRACTICAL IMPLEMENTATION of spec/19-topology.md's coordination framework. The build lock maps to the coupling matrix: agents sharing CARGO_TARGET_DIR have coupling=1.0 on the build artifact. The fix maps to Π (assignment policy): assign agents to NON-OVERLAPPING file sets + SEPARATE target dirs. The deeper fix maps to ADR-TOPOLOGY-004 (topology-as-compilation): we can DERIVE the optimal agent assignment from the task dependency graph, because tasks trace to spec elements which trace to implementation files. The compilation pipeline: Task graph → file coupling IR → agent partition → assignment with disjoint file sets + per-agent target dirs → parallel edit → sequential verify. This is Stage 3 functionality, but the COLD_START algorithm for n<=5 agents is achievable at Stage 1. The key insight: CALM stratification means EDITING is Tier M (monotonic, parallel) and VERIFICATION is Tier NM (non-monotonic, sequential barrier). We already proved this empirically: 3 agents editing different files in parallel works; they only conflict at build time.; Session entity: :task/t-920174ac; Session entity: :task/t-0550c415; Session entity: :task/t-3c5b1bb7; CRITICAL INSIGHT: The agent (me) designed a topology solution from scratch without querying the store for EXISTING spec elements that cover the EXACT same formalism. spec/19-topology.md has 16 INVs, 7 ADRs, coupling matrices, CALM stratification, compilation pipelines — all directly relevant. But I didn't run 'braid query' to check what already exists before designing. This is EPISTEMIC DIVERGENCE (type 1 in the reconciliation taxonomy): agent knowledge diverged from store knowledge. The store KNEW about topology formalism; I didn't query it. ROOT CAUSE: The seed output at session start didn't surface spec/19-topology.md as relevant to 'build lock contention' because the semantic association is indirect (build lock → coordination → topology). The seed uses keyword matching, not causal reasoning. DEEPER ROOT CAUSE: There's no mechanism for the system to say 'before you design something new, check if the spec already covers it.' The SFE system catches this at task creation (it flagged missing INV-TOPOLOGY-*), but by then the design is already done. We need SFE-like checking at DESIGN time, not just task-creation time.; Session entity: :task/t-b9aba17a; Session entity: :task/t-a4865988; Session entity: :task/t-ff0770e8; Session entity: :task/t-22d34485; Session entity: :task/t-b8a46ac4; PSR AUDIT — 3 issues found. (1) PSR-1 uses TF-IDF-like scoring but the spec statements are SHORT (typically 20-50 words). TF-IDF works best on longer documents. For short text, EXACT KEYWORD OVERLAP is more effective than TF-IDF weighting. Simpler: lowercase both texts, split into words, count intersection. Score = |intersection| / sqrt(|input_words| * |spec_words|). This is cosine similarity on bag-of-words — well-understood, fast, works on short text. (2) PSR-2 says 'wire into footer for all text-bearing commands' but the footer is ALREADY complex (M(t), next action, contextual hint). Adding spec references risks OVERLOADING the footer. FIX: Spec references should be on a SEPARATE line, clearly labeled 'Spec:'. And should ONLY appear when relevance score > 0.3 (strong match), not > 0.1 (weak noise). (3) PSR-3 wiring into seed Constraints: seed already has a constraint cap of 5. Adding PSR matches could push total constraints past the cap. FIX: PSR matches should be MERGED with existing constraints by deduplication, not appended. If a PSR match is already in the graph-proximity constraints, skip it. Only ADD genuinely new spec elements that the graph missed.; RADICAL INNOVATION: Proactive Spec Retrieval (PSR) — make EVERY braid command surface related spec elements, not just observe. When braid task create mentions 'build lock', surface INV-TOPOLOGY-004. When braid seed --task 'fix coordination', include topology spec in Constraints section. When braid next shows a task about 'coupling', append 'See: spec/19-topology.md'. This turns the spec from a PASSIVE DOCUMENT into an ACTIVE PARTICIPANT in every interaction. The system doesn't wait for the agent to query — it INJECTS spec awareness. Implementation: lightweight keyword extraction from command input text, fuzzy match against :spec/statement index, top-3 matches appended to guidance footer. Existing infrastructure: extract_spec_ids (keyword extraction), attribute_datoms (indexed lookup), build_command_footer (footer injection). ~50 LOC wiring. The compound effect: every session, every command, the agent is reminded of relevant spec. Over time, agents internalize spec structure because it's ALWAYS present. This is the self-improvement loop applied to SPEC AWARENESS.; Session entity: :task/t-a2117f50; SESSION 025 FINAL DEEP REFLECTION: 5 friction points, each revealing a deeper architectural principle. (1) Task title-as-description: the task entity has ONE text field for everything. This violates the datom model's own principle — attributes should be atomic. Title, description, acceptance, and tracing are 4 DIFFERENT concerns crammed into one attribute. Fix: decompose into :task/title (50 chars), :task/description, :task/acceptance, :task/traces-to. (2) Agent coordination fragility: agents compete for cargo build lock because they all share CARGO_TARGET_DIR. Fix: per-agent target dirs or agent-aware build coordination. (3) R(t) leaf-node problem: 270+ leaf tasks with near-zero centrality. The graph metrics assume a CONNECTED graph but most tasks are leaves hanging off EPICs. Fix: normalize impact within EPIC groups, not globally. (4) Harvest scan cost: O(N) full scan × M passes = O(NM). At 16K datoms with 5+ passes, this is ~80K datom reads per harvest. Fix: indexed scans via AVET/LIVE view instead of full iteration. (5) No session summary: the system knows what happened (tx log, task closures, observations) but doesn't SYNTHESIZE it. Fix: braid session summary that aggregates session-bounded activity into a structured report.; Session entity: :task/t-1a196a01; RESEARCH DIRECTIVE: Deep exploration of spec/19-topology.md as it relates to the agent build-lock contention problem. The build lock is a SYMPTOM of a deeper issue: we have no coordination topology for multi-agent development. Currently agents coordinate implicitly (shared filesystem, shared cargo lock, shared git repo) with no explicit protocol. spec/19-topology.md defines the formal framework: T = (G, Φ, Σ, Π) where G is agent graph, Φ is merge policy, Σ is scaling, Π is assignment. The build-lock problem maps to Φ (merge frequency) and Π (what each agent works on). The edit/verify separation maps to CALM stratification (ADR-TOPOLOGY-002): editing is monotonic (Tier M, parallel), verification is non-monotonic (Tier NM, sequential barrier). The topology-as-compilation insight (ADR-TOPOLOGY-004) means we can DERIVE the optimal agent assignment from the task dependency graph — assigning agents to non-overlapping file sets.; Session entity: :task/t-86074c4e; Session entity: :task/t-5726f00d\nSession entity: :task/t-0a93e26e; Session entity: :task/t-acb4dbec; Session entity: :task/t-29d864b1" :op :assert}
